{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491301"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"908"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/908"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.3,0.16,0.04,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109039"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/908"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91405"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109039"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner after an episode of rapid onset, sharp right upper quadrant pain this morning that lasted for about 20 minutes and then subsided. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min and blood pressure 140/100mmHg. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. The practitioner arranges a non-contrast CT scan and a representative slice is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","CT angiogram","Contrast-enhanced CT","MRI scan","Ultrasound imaging in one year"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an abdominal aortic aneurysm (Image). This is almost certainly an incidental finding, as the patient\u0027s symptoms would be most characteristic of an episode of biliary colic. Whilst a CT scan is not the ideal investigation for presumed biliary disease, the reality is that this form of imaging is often done in these circumstances. With regards to the aneurysm, depending on its size and rate of expansion the advice given to the patient will vary. As measured on the scale shown on the CT scan, this aneurysm is less than 50 mm diameter. Aneurysms less than 50 mm diameter have a \u0026lt;1% chance of rupture, but those where the rate of expansion exceeds 10 mm in 12 months should be considered for repair. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient can be kept under active surveillance and \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound examination in one year\u003C/strong\u003E would be quite appropriate. Although there is variation in the international guidelines for the surveillance of asymptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysms (AAAs), the 2024 European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) guidelines are most widely followed, including in Australia and New Zealand. The ESVS guidelines recommend the following monitoring schedule for asymptomatic patients according to AAA diameter:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E25 - 29 mm: ultrasound every five years\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E30 - 39 mm: ultrasound every three years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E40 - 49 mm (men) or 40 \u2013 44 mm (women): annual ultrasound\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226550 mm (men) or \u226545 mm (women): ultrasound every six months.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf no other pathology is found to clearly explain the patient\u0027s symptoms, then a \u003Cstrong\u003Etriple phase CT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate, to more formally assess the aortic aneurysm. Apart from its invasive nature, a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is not going to add anything to the immediate management and is unlikely to yield any more useful information that would be obtained with a contrast CT. An \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E scan will not provide any additional information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the patient should certainly be given \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance \u003C/strong\u003Ewith regards to the unlikely serious significance of the aortic aneurysm, such reassurance should be bolstered with the plan of follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysms of \u003C54 mm in men can be kept under regular (ultrasound) surveillance."],"references":["ESVS 2024 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm. In: European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://esvs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/ESVS-2024-AAA-Guidelines.pdf","Kent KC. Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms. N Engl J Med 2014;371:2101-08. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25427112/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91405"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"908"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14922"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20628"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14922"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com